<DOC><DOCNO> AP890209-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0932EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     02-09 0186</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0192</SECOND><HEAD>Gunmen Kill Roman Catholic Man</HEAD><DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A gunman firing from amotorcycle shot to death a Roman Catholic pedestrian today, policesaid, near a central Belfast square notorious for sectarian killings.   Two helmeted men rode up to 33-year-old Tony Fusco in a streetoff Smithfield Square, and one of them fired several shots fromclose range, said police Sgt. Michael Glover.   Fusco lived in the Falls, a Catholic district in west Belfast,and police found a motorbike apparently abandoned by the assailantsin the adjoining Shankill, a Protestant district.   Fusco had no connection with the security forces and his killingbore the hallmarks of a sectarian attack, Glover said.   No group immediately claimed responsibility.   On Jan. 18, two masked gunmen killed a Roman Catholic worker in astore in Smithfield Market near the Protestant and Catholic enclavesof west Belfast.   More than 2,700 people have been killed in nearly 20 years ofpolitical and sectarian violence in the British-ruled province.   The Irish Republican Army is fighting to end British rule andunite the province with the Irish Republic.</TEXT></DOC>